ted-printable\r\n\r\nThere is always freewill, infact a general and good thumb-rule is that as l=\r\nong as one is wondering (philosophically at least) whether freewill exists =\r\nor not, practically one has freewill and would do good to use it appropriat=\r\nely. To be beyond freewill, well, one just knows organically as that happen=\r\ns. As long as there is a mental/emotional association with an action, then =\r\nthere is the possibility of reaping some reaction - good or bad - for that =\r\naction. Therefore it but vital to use discrimination in action as far as po=\r\nssible.\nWhen we are advised to be spontaneous, we must understand that ther=\r\ne is, simplistically speaking, two basic division inside a human being - th=\r\ne surperficial/surface personality which we all have, and a deeper being wh=\r\nich has to be found (by sadhana). The surface personality is an aggregation=\r\n/accumulation of various conditionings and tendencies gathered in one or ma=\r\nny lifetimes. There is nothing particularly divine about it. When we functi=\r\non through this, which most of us do, we are leading a normal life. But whe=\r\nn through the process of sadhana - any sadhana that is working - we are abl=\r\ne to go deeper with and function from THAT Being which lies hidden behind o=\r\nur daily personality, THEN the matter of spontaneity actually comes up. Eve=\r\nn in ordinary existence that Being keeps sending out a guidance to us but d=\r\nue to various aquired mental and emotional tendencies we keep ignoring its =\r\nadvice. The more we ignore, the more it recedes to the background and its v=\r\noice gets overpowered by the clamour of out mental fluctuations. This is wh=\r\nat is known in normal language as the Viveka - discrimination. But when by =\r\nsadhana a seeker learns to go deeper, the first step for which maybe calmin=\r\ng the external mind and emotions, then one can eventually discover a clear =\r\nand spontaneous and sure guidance, for it uses not the mental reason, or is=\r\n not driven by emotions vacillations at all, but is connected in some pecul=\r\niar way to the Divine. This spontenity is prized. Then one may say, as one =\r\ngoes deeper and this state of living from within becomes more settled, that=\r\n one is but a mere instrument in the flow of the Divine Rhythm. Before that=\r\n, we are all subject to out free wills and repercussions thereof.=C2=A0\nOft=\r\nen by a generic use of the term spontaneity, or inner voice, we mean a norm=\r\nal reaction that we have been inculcating to situations and which has becom=\r\ne so ingrained that we do not even think before we act into it. For example=\r\n an aggressive person whose first reaction to every situaiton is an act of =\r\naggression, will always *spontaneously* behave that way whenever a difficul=\r\nt life situation comes up. Or an escapist who has been escaping all his lif=\r\ne will first automatically think of escaping from a difficult situation bec=\r\nause thath is what his conditioned response is. =C2=A0That too is spontaneo=\r\nus, but spiritually useless. If anything it reinforces the tendencies that =\r\nwe live by. The spiritual spontaneity arises as one goes deeper within, whi=\r\nch of course is not easy and needs lot of practice and effort, unless one i=\r\ns very very pure (internally), which is too rare in this age..\nIMO the line=\r\n from the Aghora book should be taken as an attitude to be inculcated as a =\r\nmethod of sadhana. To develop surrender, and as we try we may find resistan=\r\nce - due to deep conditioned responses - which means we still have to make =\r\nconscious freewill choices and live by them, and also is an indication that=\r\n we may need to work on perfecting surrender. If surrender is truly perfect=\r\n, there is no need for anything. But then, as in all things in spiritual li=\r\nfe, none of it is easy, and we have to keep trying and trying..\nBTW one of =\r\nthe very typical sadhanas is to imagine the form of the choosen deity in th=\r\ne heart and meditate thus... if this practice is done daily, with patience,=\r\n and sincerity, it can, so people say, bring many benefits eventually.\nHope=\r\n this helps.\n-Regards=C2=A0Rajarshi\n\n\n\n=C2=A0\nI have a hundred lives before=\r\n me yet/ To grasp thee in, O spirit ethereal, / Be sure I will with heart i=\r\nnsatiate/ Pursue thee like a hunter through them all. -Sri Aurobindo\n\n     =\r\n From: &quot;puloma_dasgupta@... [vedic-wisdom]&quot; &lt;vedic-wisdom@yahoogroups=\r\n.com&gt;\n To: vedic-wisdom@yahoogroups.com \n Sent: Tuesday, 9 February 2016 2:=\r\n58 AM\n Subject: [vedic-wisdom] Surrender\n   \n=C2=A0   &quot;Arguably the most fu=\r\nndamental of these realisations is this: the essence of living with reality=\r\n is to continually surrender to what is. You have already created your own =\r\npersonal universe with your karmas and now you must live in it. (...) If ha=\r\nving decided to surrender you are willing to keep surrendering, and then yo=\r\nu surrender some more, you will simplify your personal choreography to the =\r\nmore manageable - if still convoluted - process of resolving how, when, and=\r\n what to yield.&quot;\n - Robert Svoboda, The Law of Karma, Pg 9\nFor those who ma=\r\nke it a point to cooperate with the Divine/Cosmic Will and flow with it rat=\r\nher than force their free will (if there is one) on it, do you try to guard=\r\n against your tendency to negative/undesirable actions if they come up? How=\r\n do you do so while still being spontaneous? Is the practice of self-awaren=\r\ness antithetical to surrender?\n\n  #yiv4114009502 #yiv4114009502 -- #yiv4114=\r\n009502ygrp-mkp {border:1px solid #d8d8d8;font-family:Arial;margin:10px 0;pa=\r\ndding:0 10px;}#yiv4114009502 #yiv4114009502ygrp-mkp hr {border:1px solid #d=\r\n8d8d8;}#yiv4114009502 #yiv4114009502ygrp-mkp #yiv4114009502hd {color:#628c2=\r\na;font-size:85%;font-weight:700;line-height:122%;margin:10px 0;}#yiv4114009=\r\n502 #yiv411400950